Roe and I met at Print Space darkroom 25 years ago (what??) and I took my first picture of him a couple months later. I thought I knew everything I needed to know about my friend until we started our Q+A for @cultured_mag. Topics range from: The South, Mom and Dad, Gursky and Ruff, Oakleys and Olive Garden, and his must-have new monograph American Polychronic. And if that ain't enough, go see his two NYC exhibitions opening tonight. Congratulations Roe. Love you man!

Our dear friend Christa Aboitiz had been telling us about Lenny Steinberg for years: her idiosyncratic masterpiece on Venice Beach—three doors down from Frank Gehry’s Norton house—and Lenny’s unsung furniture line from the 60s, Vivid, which dubbed her “The Mirror Queen”! 
 
Thank you @sarah_c_douglas and @michaelreynoldsnyc @wallpapermag for including Lenny in your fantastic America issue.  
 
Don’t miss our short film on Lenny @cottage8films 
 
You’ll fall in love with her, I promise.

When I was 21 or 22 I sort-of accidentally got to sit in on Nan Goldin presenting “The Ballad” to small group, with a slide projector, talking us through every picture—something I will never forget!  
 
So getting the chance to photograph Nan and the activist group she founded, PAIN, in Nan’s living room, where they held their meetings, was a thrill the 21 year old me could never have predicted. And it was an honor: “All the Beauty and the Bloodshed” is an equally unforgettable account of what Nan and PAIN have accomplished. Bravo to you all! 
 
Thank you @nangoldinstudio for welcoming me, again!  
Thank you @noemibonazzi—who I may have first seen in Nan’s slideshow all those years ago?—for paving the way and @michaelreynolds for brainstorming this!  
Thank you, as always, @sarah_c_douglas + @wallpapermag!

Houses built by architects for themselves often push ideas further than they ever could for a client. This one takes the cake! 
 
Christian Wassmann has built a 50’ x 50’ house around a bluestone boulder at the top of a mountain in the Catskills. There’s a curved glass wall that surrounds the rock and radial lines—the roof beams, interior walls, and even the dividers in the kitchen drawers— all converge back at the boulder. It’s insanely incredible. Love this house. You rock @christianwassmann! Thank you @kateorne for the plum assignment for @upstate_diary!

Casa de Vidro by Lina Bo Bardi. An Italian born architect working in Brazil, Lina designed the Casa for herself in 1951. Another example of a spectacular house—with no client to please but  herself @institutobardi.  
 
Thank you @danipizetta and @solcamacho for making this happen and thank you @kateorne for publishing it in the one and only @upstate_diary xx
More from the mind-bending Lina Bo Bardi. Being at the SESC Pompéia feels like the future—as conceived in 1982—that I wish had been built everywhere!

@fireleibaez is🔥 *This is the first post of Wendy Goodman Appreciation Week! Stay tuned to this channel for other recent artists’ homes and studio visits, all gems, all thanks to the one and only @dhwendygoodman! With a giant shout out, of course, to @jodyquon  
@nymag

Neil Jenney’s home and studio is the second post of Wendy Goodman Appreciation week!  Take it away Wendy:  
  
“You see, I have this problem,” Neil Jenney tells me when I meet him at the Wooster Street end of his 11,000-square-foot full-floor Soho loft. “I have a landline telephone, and I tell people, ‘Let it ring because I have to run down the block to answer the phone.’ ” That phone is located in what Jenney calls his “everything” room, which is at the West Broadway end of the space that he bought for $36,000 in 1973.  
  
You can hear @neiljenneyofficial tell it in the short video at the end of carousel.   
🙏⚡️❤️ @dhwendygoodman + @jodyquon + @nymag

If you don’t know @dhwendygoodman, she is the longtime design editor of New York Magazine and publishes some of the most extraordinary spaces that somehow only she could wrangle. They are decidedly all very “Wendy.” 
 
Another case in point: a lighthouse turned into into a solar and wind powered artist residency by @randypolumbo that is as amazing as it is improbable. 
 
Thank you for having us Randy; you are a mad genius!
There is only one Andres Serrano and this is where he lives. Another religious experience thanks to, you guessed it, @dhwendygoodman @jodyquon @nymag

To cap off Wendy Goodman Appreciation Week, I leave you with Thomas Lollar’s 500 sq ft “one bedroom museum.”   
  
Lollar, an artist and educator, would point to any single object in his collection—a mirror, a spoon, a coin—and share its history and provenance, regaling us with ancient stories of “long-ago everyday lives.”   
  
Another quintessentially @dhwendygoodman story: you can’t really believe it until you see it, and you will not see it anywhere else!  Thank you Wendy and Jody and New York Magazine for the chance to document how New Yorkers live today.

There is nothing that I have ever shot that has made my theater-loving Jewish mother kvell more than this!   
   
Shot in September at the Lyceum Theater for T’s Holiday issue cover, @nytimes chief theater critic Jesse Green writes about "how Jewish people came to establish American theater as we know it.” I’ve never quite experienced this particular combination of warmth, ceremony and laughter on set.   
   
Thank you so much @hanyayanagihara @kurtsoller @patrickli__ @nadiavellam @jamiebsims @carterblove @tmagazine   
   
And a huge thanks also to Christine Jones (@dogheart7)—a Tony award winning scenic designer—who literally set the stage to make magic!   
   
Special bonus: the legendary Joel Grey (@joelgnyc) switched roles with me for a final cover try. 🤍

To see Dana Schutz at work just once is a thrill, but I have been beyond lucky: for the past 18 months I’ve been regularly documenting Dana as she made the mind-bending paintings and sculptures now on view at @davidzwirner for one more week, through December 16th.   
  
But don’t listen to me, take it from @jerrysaltz: “Her more ardent paintings left me speechless: huge, luridly iridescent moonscapes, slathered surfaces piled up with greasy paint, giant marionette-like figures with spidery limbs and oversize heads. Her ambition is massive, Kiefer like. There are Olympian battle scenes and brawls, as well as tense, quiet interludes in between…Why not call @danaschutzart - enormous black bronze sprawling lunar moonscape masterpiece of carnage, contagion, neighing steeds, strange birds, wailing figures, crutches and detritus atop a mound of discarded debris a masterpiece of modern sculpture. At @davidzwirner. See it. An impossibility come life. Schutz, 47, is one of our best sculptors. Be repulsed and awed by the sublimity. I am.”  
  
Thank you Dana and @ryanjohnsonstudio for opening your studio doors to me, something I will never take for granted!
